---
/* eslint-disable astro/no-set-html-directive */
import SubpageLayout from "../../layouts/SubpageLayout.astro";

export function getStaticPaths() {
  return [
    {
      params: { slug: "souk-survival-tips" },
      props: {
        title: "10 Souk Survival Tips for First-Time Marrakech Travelers",
        date: "June 25, 2026",
        author: "Omar Bennani",
        readTime: "5 min read",
        category: "Guides",
        image: "https://assets.codepen.io/3685267/timed-cards-3.jpg",
        content: `
          <p class="lead text-lg text-white/80 leading-relaxed mb-6 font-[Outfit]">Marrakech's historic souks are a dream for shoppers, but they can be overwhelming. Learn how to navigate the narrow alleys, haggle like a local, and identify real spices.</p>
          
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-[Oswald] font-semibold text-[#ecad29] uppercase tracking-wider mt-8 mb-4">1. Know Your Way, or Accept the Maze</h2>
          <p class="leading-relaxed mb-6 text-white/70">The Medina is designed like a labyrinth. Getting lost isn't a mistake; it's part of the itinerary. Download offline maps like Google Maps or Maps.me beforehand, but don't hesitate to enjoy the random alleys you find.</p>
          
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-[Oswald] font-semibold text-[#ecad29] uppercase tracking-wider mt-8 mb-4">2. The Art of Haggling (Derb Negotiation)</h2>
          <p class="leading-relaxed mb-6 text-white/70">Bargaining is a social custom. Start by offering 40-50% of the vendor's initial price, then negotiate slowly upwards. Always smile, keep it light, and be ready to walk away if the price doesn't suit you.</p>
          
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-[Oswald] font-semibold text-[#ecad29] uppercase tracking-wider mt-8 mb-4">3. Stay Polite but Assertive</h2>
          <p class="leading-relaxed mb-6 text-white/70">You will be invited into shops constantly. A polite "La, Shukran" (No, thank you) with a smile and a hand over your heart is respected and will keep vendors from following you.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-[Oswald] font-semibold text-[#ecad29] uppercase tracking-wider mt-8 mb-4">4. Bring Cash (Dirhams)</h2>
          <p class="leading-relaxed mb-6 text-white/70">Credit cards are rarely accepted inside the small souk stalls. Carry small denomination banknotes (10, 20, 50 Dirhams) for easy transactions and tips.</p>
        `,
      },
    },
    {
      params: { slug: "sahara-desert-camping" },
      props: {
        title: "Sleeping in the Sahara: What to Expect in a Desert Camp",
        date: "June 18, 2026",
        author: "Yasmine Mansouri",
        readTime: "7 min read",
        category: "Adventure",
        image: "https://assets.codepen.io/3685267/timed-cards-6.jpg",
        content: `
          <p class="lead text-lg text-white/80 leading-relaxed mb-6 font-[Outfit]">A trek into the dunes of Erg Chebbi is an essential Moroccan experience. Here is everything you need to know about luxury camps, desert weather, camel riding, and starry nights.</p>
          
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-[Oswald] font-semibold text-[#ecad29] uppercase tracking-wider mt-8 mb-4">1. Erg Chebbi vs Erg Chigaga</h2>
          <p class="leading-relaxed mb-6 text-white/70">Erg Chebbi (near Merzouga) features towering, easily accessible orange dunes with excellent camp facilities. Erg Chigaga is more remote and wild, requiring a 4x4 ride to reach deep desert isolation.</p>
          
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-[Oswald] font-semibold text-[#ecad29] uppercase tracking-wider mt-8 mb-4">2. The Desert Camp Setup</h2>
          <p class="leading-relaxed mb-6 text-white/70">Modern luxury camps feature private bathrooms, running hot water, and king-size beds inside heavy canvas tents. Traditional camps offer simpler shared setups, offering a rustic experience under the stars.</p>
          
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-[Oswald] font-semibold text-[#ecad29] uppercase tracking-wider mt-8 mb-4">3. Temperatures Fluctuations</h2>
          <p class="leading-relaxed mb-6 text-white/70">The desert gets surprisingly cold at night. Even in hot summer months, temperatures drop rapidly once the sun goes down. Pack warm layers, socks, and a fleece jacket for campfire storytelling.</p>
        `,
      },
    },
    {
      params: { slug: "chefchaouen-photography-guide" },
      props: {
        title: "Exploring the Blue Pearl: A Chefchaouen Photography Guide",
        date: "June 12, 2026",
        author: "Karim Alaoui",
        readTime: "4 min read",
        category: "Photography",
        image: "https://assets.codepen.io/3685267/timed-cards-2.jpg",
        content: `
          <p class="lead text-lg text-white/80 leading-relaxed mb-6 font-[Outfit]">Chefchaouen is a photographer's paradise. We share the exact coordinates of the most iconic blue staircases, best sunrise views, and tips for photographing locals respectfully.</p>
          
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-[Oswald] font-semibold text-[#ecad29] uppercase tracking-wider mt-8 mb-4">1. Catch the Golden Hour</h2>
          <p class="leading-relaxed mb-6 text-white/70">The best lighting inside the blue alleys occurs in the early morning (7:00 AM - 9:00 AM) before the sun gets too harsh. The alleys are also completely empty at this hour, allowing clean landscape shots.</p>
          
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-[Oswald] font-semibold text-[#ecad29] uppercase tracking-wider mt-8 mb-4">2. Respecting Locals</h2>
          <p class="leading-relaxed mb-6 text-white/70">Always ask permission before taking photos of local shopkeepers or children. A simple "S'il vous plaît?" or "Moulana?" with a camera gesture goes a long way. Many will happily agree or politely decline.</p>
          
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-[Oswald] font-semibold text-[#ecad29] uppercase tracking-wider mt-8 mb-4">3. Iconic Blue Alleys</h2>
          <p class="leading-relaxed mb-6 text-white/70">While the whole Medina is blue, Calle Sidi Buchuka and El Asri are famous for their steps lined with colored flower pots. Wander off the main shopping streets to discover hidden arches.</p>
        `,
      },
    },
    {
      params: { slug: "moroccan-mint-tea-etiquette" },
      props: {
        title: "Moroccan Mint Tea Etiquette: More Than Just a Drink",
        date: "June 05, 2026",
        author: "Fatima Zahra",
        readTime: "3 min read",
        category: "Culture",
        image: "https://assets.codepen.io/3685267/timed-cards-1.jpg",
        content: `
          <p class="lead text-lg text-white/80 leading-relaxed mb-6 font-[Outfit]">Known as 'Berber Whiskey', Moroccan mint tea is a symbol of hospitality. Discover the history behind the brew, the pouring technique, and how to accept tea gracefully.</p>
          
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-[Oswald] font-semibold text-[#ecad29] uppercase tracking-wider mt-8 mb-4">1. The Sign of Hospitality</h2>
          <p class="leading-relaxed mb-6 text-white/70">If you enter a shop, home, or riad, you will be offered hot tea. Refusing it is considered impolite. Always accept at least one glass to honor your host's hospitality.</p>
          
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-[Oswald] font-semibold text-[#ecad29] uppercase tracking-wider mt-8 mb-4">2. The High Pour</h2>
          <p class="leading-relaxed mb-6 text-white/70">Tea is poured from a height of up to a meter. This is not just for show; the high pour aerates the hot tea, creating a beautiful foam (regga) at the top of the glass, and cools it down to drinking temperature.</p>
          
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-[Oswald] font-semibold text-[#ecad29] uppercase tracking-wider mt-8 mb-4">3. Sweetness & Mint</h2>
          <p class="leading-relaxed mb-6 text-white/70">Moroccan tea is traditionally brewed with green gunpowder tea leaves, large chunks of sugar, and fresh spearmint leaves. It is served hot and sweet, ideal for hydration under the sun.</p>
        `,
      },
    },
  ];
}

const { title, date, author, readTime, category, image, content } = Astro.props;
---

<SubpageLayout title={title}>
  <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-12 pb-24">
    <!-- Back to Blog Link -->
    <a
      class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-[#ecad29] hover:text-white transition-colors mb-8"
      href="/blog"
    >
      <svg
        class="h-4 w-4"
        fill="none"
        stroke="currentColor"
        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
      >
        <path
          d="M10 19l-7-7m0 0l7-7m-7 7h18"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
          stroke-width="2"
        ></path>
      </svg>
      Back to Blog Hub
    </a>

    <!-- Blog Header -->
    <header
      class="mb-10"
      data-animate="fade-up"
    >
      <span
        class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-[#ecad29] font-semibold bg-[#ecad29]/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-md border border-[#ecad29]/20 mr-2"
      >
        {category}
      </span>
      <h1
        class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-[Oswald] font-bold text-white uppercase tracking-wide mt-6 mb-4 leading-tight"
      >
        {title}
      </h1>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-4 text-xs text-white/40">
        <span>By {author}</span>
        <span>•</span>
        <span>{date}</span>
        <span>•</span>
        <span>{readTime}</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <!-- Featured Image -->
    <div
      class="relative h-112.5 overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-white/5 mb-12 shadow-xl"
      data-animate="fade-up"
    >
      <div class="h-full w-full overflow-hidden">
        <img
          alt={title}
          class="w-full h-full scale-120 object-cover"
          data-animate="parallax"
          src={image}
        />
      </div>
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-linear-to-t from-[#1a1a1a] via-transparent to-transparent">
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Article Content -->
    <div
      class="prose prose-invert max-w-none text-white/70 font-[Inter] leading-relaxed"
      data-animate="fade-up"
      set:html={content}
    />
  </article>
</SubpageLayout>
